examples: He is overparticular about his diet and workout routine.
She is overparticular when it comes to organising her work desk.

data.etymology: The term 'overparticular' originates from the prefix 'over-', meaning 'too much', and 'particular', which refers to 'attention to detail'. Together, they form 'overparticular', signifying someone who is excessively concerned with minor details or rules.
data.englishDefinition: Excessively concerned with minor details or rules; fastidious.

examples: This is the original version of the document.
The artist's original works are highly valued.

data.etymology: From Old French 'original', from Latin 'originem' meaning 'beginning, source, birth'
data.englishDefinition: Present or existing from the beginning; first or earliest. Or created directly and personally by a particular artist; not a copy or imitation

examples: 이 PDF는 수정 가능한 형식입니다.
그는 수정 가능한 계획을 세웠다.

data.etymology: From the Latin word 'modificabilis', from the verb 'modificare' meaning 'to limit, measure off, or moderate'.
data.englishDefinition: Capable of being modified; subject to change; alterable.

examples: His worldliness made him a great diplomat.
Her lack of worldliness was evident in her naivety.

data.etymology: From the English words 'world' + '-ly' (adjective suffix) + '-ness' (suffix indicating state or condition). Originally from Old English 'weorold' meaning 'human existence, the affairs of life'.
data.englishDefinition: The quality of being experienced, sophisticated, and worldly; cosmopolitan.

examples: PDF에서 필요한 정보를 찾아내다
특정 페이지를 찾아내다

data.etymology: Locate comes from the Latin word 'locatus', the past participle of the verb 'locare' which means 'to place'. It was first used in English in the 15th century.
data.englishDefinition: To discover the exact place or position of something

examples: They conferred about the problem.
The university conferred an honorary degree on her.
We need to confer on this matter.

data.etymology: Middle English: from Latin conferre, from con- ‘together’ + ferre ‘bring’.
data.englishDefinition: To consult together; compare opinions; deliberate; to bestow or grant

examples: She is a renowned author in her field.
The city is renowned for its beautiful architecture.
He is renowned for his expert knowledge in the field of PDF extraction.

data.etymology: From Middle English, from Anglo-Norman renouned, past participle of renouner (“to proclaim”), from Old French renomer (“to name, nominate again”).
data.englishDefinition: Famous, celebrated, or well-known for some quality or achievement.

examples: His shirt was immaculate.
The room was in immaculate order.

data.etymology: Early 15th century, from Latin immaculatus 'unstained', from in- 'not' + maculatus 'spotted', from the verb maculare 'to stain'.
data.englishDefinition: Perfectly clean, neat, or tidy; free from flaws or mistakes; perfect

examples: He made a precipitous decision without considering the consequences.
The precipitous cliff was a danger to the hikers.

data.etymology: From Latin 'praecipitium' meaning 'a steep place', and from 'praecipitare' to 'fall headlong, hurl down'
data.englishDefinition: Extremely steep, abrupt or hasty

examples: Stars are luminous bodies.
The room was filled with a luminous glow.

data.etymology: From Latin 'luminosus', from 'lumen' meaning 'light'
data.englishDefinition: Full of or shedding light; bright or shining, especially in the dark.

examples: In the process of PDF extraction, the data is expanded into a readable format.
The company is planning to expand its operations to Asia.
As the balloon heats up, it starts to expand.

data.etymology: Expand comes from the Latin 'expandere' which means 'to spread out', from 'ex-' ('out') and 'pandere' ('to spread').
data.englishDefinition: To increase in size, volume, quantity, or scope; enlarge.

examples: He embarked on a lucrative career as a stand-up comedian.
They do a lot of business in lucrative overseas markets.

data.etymology: Middle English, from Latin lucratus, past participle of lucrari to gain, from lucrum
data.englishDefinition: producing a great deal of profit

examples: 그녀는 숫자가 매겨지지 않은 페이지를 뒤적거렸다.
숫자가 매겨지지 않은 별들이 하늘을 밝혔다.

data.etymology: Derived from the prefix 'un-' meaning 'not' + 'numbered', past participle of 'number'. First known use in the 14th century.
data.englishDefinition: Not numbered or counted; too many to be numbered or counted.

examples: The elephant was enormous in size.
The enormous tree overshadowed the small house.

data.etymology: Enormous comes from the Latin word 'enormis', where 'e' means 'out of' and 'norma' means 'rule or pattern'. This word originally meant 'irregular' or 'unusual', but in English, it has come to mean 'extremely large'.
data.englishDefinition: Very large in size, quantity, or extent.

definitions.definition: 두 개 이상의 문장, 구, 단어를 연결하는 데 사용되는 단어 또는 구.
examples: She failed the test, 'but' she still expects to pass the course.
I want to play the game, 'and' I also want to win.

data.etymology: From Middle English conjunccioun, from Latin coniunctiō (“joining together”), from coniungō.
data.englishDefinition: A word used to connect clauses or sentences or to coordinate words in the same clause.

examples: These techniques constitute a new approach.
Women constitute about 5% of the police force.

data.etymology: From the Latin 'constituere', which means 'to set up, establish'.
data.englishDefinition: To make up or form something.

examples: The company had to suspend its operations due to a financial crisis.
The teacher may suspend the student for bad behavior.
The game was suspended due to rain.

data.etymology: From Latin 'suspendere', from 'sub-' (meaning under) + 'pendere' (meaning to hang). It came into existence in English around the 13th century.
data.englishDefinition: To stop something from being active, either temporarily or permanently.

examples: They set out to conquer the world.
He conquered all his fears.

data.etymology: Middle English: from Old French conquerre, based on Latin conquirere ‘seek out or search’, from con- ‘altogether’ + quaerere ‘ask, seek’. The spelling with -o- in the first syllable was influenced by Latin words beginning with con-.
data.englishDefinition: To take control or possession of foreign land, or a group of people, by force.

examples: 그의 놀라운 변화에 모두가 놀랐다.
그 결과는 정말로 놀라웠다.

data.etymology: From Middle English 'surprisen', from Old French 'surprendre' (to overtake), from 'sur' (over) + 'prendre' (take). First known use in 15th century.
data.englishDefinition: Causing one to feel unexpected wonder or astonishment.

examples: He is invariably late for meetings.
The trains are invariably punctual.
She invariably forgets to call.

data.etymology: From Late Latin 'invariabilis', from in- 'not' + variabilis 'changeable'
data.englishDefinition: In every case or on every occasion; always.

examples: His arrival at the party was an inauspicious moment.
The team had an inauspicious start to the season.

data.etymology: Inauspicious comes from the Latin word 'inauspex', which means 'not observed.' It is made up of two parts: 'in-' meaning 'not,' and 'auspicium' meaning 'divination by observing the flight of birds.'
data.englishDefinition: Not conducive to success; unpromising

examples: He is overly concerned about his appearance.
You should not be overly dependent on technology.

data.etymology: Middle English: from over + -ly.
data.englishDefinition: To an excessive degree; too much or too.

examples: Can I have another piece of cake?
This is another example of PDF extraction.
I need another solution to this problem.

data.etymology: Derived from Old English 'an ōther', which means 'one of two', 'a second'
data.englishDefinition: One more, additional; different from the one or ones already mentioned or known

examples: The snake's bite is lethal.
He was convicted of lethal assault.

data.etymology: From the Latin 'letalis' or 'letal', meaning 'deadly' or 'fatal' from 'letum' or 'death'.
data.englishDefinition: causing or capable of causing death
